335":"about 1335","1209":"1209","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","1339":"1339","1306":"1306","Trevelyan, St Veep, Cornwall, England":"St Veep, Cornwall, England, United Kingdom","Cornwall, England":"Cornwall, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Trevelyan","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["Cornish: locative name from Trevelyan in Saint Veep (Cornwall)."],"variants":[{"name":"Trevillion","meanings":["Cornish: variant of   Trevillian  ."]},{"name":"Trevallion","meanings":["Cornish:  see  Trevelyan  ."]},{"name":"Trevillian","meanings":["Cornish: variant of <b>Trevelyan</b>, a habitational name from Trevelyan in Saint Veep (Cornwall). The placename derives from Middle Cornish <i>tre(f)</i> ‘estate, farmstead’ + either an unrecorded Old Cornish personal name equivalent either to Old Breton <i>Ilian</i> or the recorded Old Cornish <i>Milian</i>, with mutation of <i>m</i> to <i>v</i>. This form of the surname is very rare in Britain and Ireland. Compare   Trovillion  ."]},{"name":"Trevillyan","meanings":["Cornish:  see  Trevelyan  ."]},{"name":"Trevelyn","meanings":["Cornish:  see  Trevelyan  ."]},{"name":"Trevalion","meanings":["Cornish:  see  Trevelyan  ."]},{"name":"Trevelion","meanings":["Cornish:  see  Trevelyan  ."]}]},{"name":"Thomas","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["New Testament name, borne by one of Christ's twelve apostles, referred to as ‘Thomas, called Didymus’ (John 11:16; 20:24). <i>Didymos</i> is the Greek word for ‘twin’, and the name is the Greek form of an Aramaic byname meaning ‘twin’. The given name has always been popular throughout Christendom, in part because St Thomas's doubts have made him seem a very human character."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705191,"age":13,"year":"1315","toYear":"1317","julianDay":2201354,"title":"Famine Strikes Europe","description":"A famine caused by cold winters and wet summers across Europe caused millions to die due to starvation. Desperation from hunger caused high levels of crime, stampedes in bread lines in London, infanticide, and even cannibalism throughout Europe.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705192,"age":26,"year":"1328","julianDay":2206102,"title":"First War of Scottish Independence","description":"The First War of Scottish Independence began after England invaded Scotland in 1296. The Treaty of Edinburgh was signed in 1328 which declared peace between the two kingdoms and brought the war to an end.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705193,"age":35,"year":"1337","toYear":"1453","julianDay":2209390,"title":"The Hundred Years' War","description":"The Hundred Years' War between France and England was largely due to the question of legitimate succession to the French crown.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Thomas Trevelyan was born about 1302, in St Veep, Cornwall, England, his father, Nicholas Trevelyan, was 94 and his mother, Felicia De Bodrugan, was 59. He married Lady Alice Trevelian in 1332, in Cornwall, England. They were the parents of at least 2 sons and 1 daughter. He died in 1369, at the age of 68."},"et":{"about 1302–1369":"umbes 1302–1369","1302–1369":"1302–1369","1305–Male":"1305–Surnud","–Male":"Surnud","1306–Female":"1306–Surnud","1333–1389":"1333–1389","1335–Male":"1335–Surnud","1339–Female":"1339–Surnud","1209–1275":"1209–1275","1244–Female":"1244–Surnud","1275":"1275","1305":"1305","1337":"1337","1315":"1315","1369":"1369","1335":"1335","1302":"1302","1389":"1389","about 1339":"umbes 1339","1333":"1333","1332":"1332","1453":"1453","1244":"1244","ABT 1333":"umbes 1333","about 1301":"umbes 1301","about 1302":"umbes 1302","about 1335":"umbes 1335","1209":"1209","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","1339":"1339","1306":"1306","Trevelyan, St Veep, Cornwall, England":"St Veep, Cornwall, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Cornwall, England":"Cornwall, Inglismaa,